# Reflection on v0.1 — 2026-05-07

## Observation
After self-testing v0.1 with a real procrastivity scenario 
(avoiding paper reading by cleaning and tinkering with this very demo), 
I noticed the agent fell into what I'd call a "Socratic loop": 
it kept returning agency to me by asking "what's the smallest next step?" 
without recognizing when I had already decomposed the task sufficiently 
(I had identified opening the PDF, reading the abstract, etc.).

## Design Tension Identified
Pure autonomy-supportive scaffolds may unintentionally stall users 
who have already passed the "activation" threshold and now need 
*forward momentum* rather than further reflection. The prompt 
optimizes for non-directive tone but lacks a "progression detection" 
mechanism.

## Implication for v0.2
The next iteration should explore:
1. How to detect when decomposition is "sufficient"
2. How to transition from reflective questioning to 
   gentle forward-pointing without violating autonomy
3. Whether literature on scaffolding fading (Wood, Bruner & Ross) 
   offers a model for this transition

## Connection to Procrastivity Framing
Interestingly, building this demo itself became a procrastivity 
behavior — preparatory work that disguised avoidance of the actual 
paper-reading task. This is consistent with my own research framing 
and provides first-person validation of the phenomenon.
